Here are a few tips for safe training nutrition that prioritize recovery.



*   Prioritize minimizing your “mileage” (overall amount of time spent at most intense pace) at practice and do the rest of your work at low intensities. You do not have to sacrifice your eating disorder recovery at the altar of wrestling performance; sacrificing your safety only sacrifices your wrestling performance.&#x20;
*   Focus on whole, unprocessed foods like fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats. They provide the nutrients you need for optimal performance.&#x20;
*   Aim to eat every 3-4 hours, and include a source of protein in each meal. This will help keep your energy levels stable and support muscle growth.&#x20;
*   Carbohydrates are your main source of energy, especially during high-intensity activities. Focus on whole, unprocessed sources like whole grains, fruits, and vegetables.&#x20;
*   Choose hydrating foods like watermelon, cucumbers, and celery, which are also low in calories. Aim to drink at least 8-10 glasses of water per day, and monitor your urine output. If your urine is pale yellow or clear, you're hydrated.&#x20;
*   The easiest way to fuel and get the needed extra nutrients is to add healthy fats like nuts, seeds, avocado, and olive oil to your meals.&#x20;

It's understandable that you might feel anxious about certain foods, especially if you're used to a more restrictive diet. Here are some suggestions for incorporating those foods into your diet.



*   Bread: Start with small amounts, such as trying a single slice of whole-grain bread with your turkey. Gradually increase the amount over time as you become more comfortable.&#x20;
*   Pasta: Choose small portion sizes and pair it with other nutrient-dense foods like vegetable-rich sauces and lean proteins.&#x20;
*   &#x20;Choose whole, minimally processed foods like fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats. They provide the nutrients you need for optimal performance.&#x20;
*   Focus on your overall lifestyle habits, including regular exercise and a balanced diet. Aim for variety and moderation in your eating, rather than drastic restrictions.
